      "content": "That skepticism is well-founded, as efficiency and wait times vary significantly depending on whether a system is fully government-run or mixes public funding with private delivery. Studies often show that countries with universal coverage have fewer untreated cases and lower overall spending, but implementation details like appointment systems and insurance co-pays heavily influence daily experience. Since there is no single \"perfect\" model, the best outcome usually depends on finding a balance that maximizes access while minimizing operational bottlenecks.",
